The main() function is the program entry point in C++.
- Signature commonly: int main() { ... return 0; }
- Controls program start and end; returning 0 signals successful execution.

It allows you to use standard library names without the std:: prefix.
- Without it: std::cout << "hi"; With it: cout << "hi";
- Avoids name collisions in large projects — prefer explicit std:: in production code.

Pseudocode: SET sum=0; FOR i FROM 1 TO N: sum = sum + i; RETURN sum.

C++ implementation:
```cpp
int sumN(int n) {
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) sum += i;
    return sum;
}
```
- Time O(n), Space O(1). Alternatively, use the formula n*(n+1)/2 for O(1) time.

Pass a lambda comparator as the third argument to std::sort.

```cpp
vector<pair<int,int>> v = {{1,5},{2,3},{3,8}};
sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](auto& a, auto& b){
    return a.second > b.second; // descending by second
});
// Result: {{3,8},{1,5},{2,3}}
```
- The comparator returns true if a should come before b.
- Custom comparators must enforce strict weak ordering (irreflexive, asymmetric, transitive).

XOR properties: a^a=0 and a^0=a.
- XOR all array elements and all numbers 1..n. Paired identical numbers cancel to 0.
- Only the missing number has no pair, so it remains.

```cpp
int xorVal = 0;
for (int x : arr) xorVal ^= x;
for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) xorVal ^= i;
// xorVal is the missing number
```
- Time O(n), Space O(1), no overflow risk.

Iterate i from 1 to √n. For each i that divides n, add both i and n/i.

```cpp
vector<int> getDivisors(int n) {
    vector<int> divs;
    for (int i = 1; i * i <= n; i++) {
        if (n % i == 0) {
            divs.push_back(i);
            if (i != n / i) divs.push_back(n / i);
        }
    }
    sort(divs.begin(), divs.end());
    return divs;
}
```
- Time O(√n + k log k) where k is divisor count. Guard i != n/i avoids duplicates for perfect squares.

next_permutation rearranges the range to the next lexicographic permutation and returns true; returns false (and resets to first permutation) when already at the maximum.

To generate all permutations:
```cpp
sort(arr.begin(), arr.end()); // start from smallest
do {
    // process arr
} while (next_permutation(arr.begin(), arr.end()));
```
- For n elements, generates n! permutations in lexicographic order.
- Time per call: O(n). Total: O(n × n!).

Check divisibility only up to √n. If any i in [2,√n] divides n, it is not prime.

```cpp
bool isPrime(int n) {
    if (n < 2) return false;
    for (int i = 2; i * i <= n; i++) {
        if (n % i == 0) return false;
    }
    return true;
}
```
- Key insight: if n has a divisor > √n, the complementary divisor < √n was already found.
- Time O(√n), Space O(1). For n=10^9, only ~31,623 checks needed.

equal_range(key) returns a pair of iterators [first, last) spanning all elements with that key.

Example with multimap:
```cpp
multimap<int,string> mm;
mm.insert({3,"Alice"}); mm.insert({3,"Bob"}); mm.insert({5,"Carol"});
auto range = mm.equal_range(3);
for (auto it=range.first; it!=range.second; it++)
    cout << it->second; // prints Alice Bob
```
- first points to the first match; second points one past the last match.
- More useful than find() when multiple values share the same key.

std::find(begin, end, value) searches linearly and returns an iterator to the first match, or end() if not found.

```cpp
vector<int> v = {4, 7, 2, 9, 1};
auto it = find(v.begin(), v.end(), 7);
if (it != v.end()) {
    cout << "Found at index " << (it - v.begin()); // 1
} else {
    cout << "Not found";
}
```
- Time O(n). For sorted data, prefer binary_search or lower_bound for O(log n).
- Always validate iterator before dereferencing.

pair<T1,T2> groups two values into one unit, accessible via .first and .second.

Example:
```cpp
vector<pair<int,string>> students;
students.push_back({1, "Alice"});
students.push_back({2, "Bob"});
for (auto& p : students)
    cout << p.first << ": " << p.second;
```
- Create with {val1, val2} or make_pair(val1, val2).
- Pairs support comparison: sorted first by .first, then by .second.
- Widely used as map entries and to return two values from a function.
